Elliotte,

A valid point.  Perhaps it would be better to have a removeListener 
method, as you mentioned before--that way, if a listener knew it wasn&#39;t 
going to be able to continue, it could remove itself from consideration, 
and the runner could decide whether there were any listeners left, and 
whether to continue.  I think this would be better than having declared 
exceptions in a listener interface.  Asking a framework to call me back, 
and then throwing an exception, feels as rude as asking a person to call 
me back, and then disconnecting my number.  How does that sound?

    David Saff

Elliotte Rusty Harold wrote:

&gt; David Saff wrote:
&gt; &gt; Elliotte,
&gt; &gt;
&gt; &gt; What would you expect the test runner to do if it caught one of these
&gt; &gt; exceptions?  In general, I would expect that listeners should not
&gt; &gt; interrupt the test execution: if they find themselves unable to do what
&gt; &gt; they want, they should quietly deal with it on their own.
&gt; &gt;
&gt;
&gt; Somebody has to listen or there&#39;s not much point to running the tests.
&gt; If the sole listener has an encountered an unrecoverable error, there&#39;s
&gt; not much point to continuing. Possibly that&#39;s not the case if there are
&gt; multiple listeners, but I think a single listener is the vast majority
&gt; of use cases.
&gt;
